body:
@dpsenner as I see it, looking at the `ServerCallContext` sources, there is no way to be sure that `RequestHeaders` is null or not -- and I see no way of setting it if it is, as it's getter-only. Am I missing something?

The "trailers" thing is precisely the same hack that works that you made, only since the trailers are instantiated by default, they're never null and what we're using is something like:

```
try
{
    return await base.UnaryServerHandler(request, context, continuation);
}
finally
{
    // Clean up after ourselves, we don't want to send that (empty) trailer to the client
    context.ResponseTrailers.Remove(metadata);
}
```

So they should get cleaned up properly (given that the `finally` block works as I expect it to). But, again as you've mentioned, this is just a working hack.

**As for the benefits of having a copy constructor on `ServiceCallContext`**, it would allow us to write something like:

```
public class ScopeAwareServiceCallContext 
{
    public IServiceScope ServiceScope { get; }

    public ScopeAwareServiceCallContext(IServiceScope serviceScope, ServiceCallContext originalContext)
        : base(originalContext) 
    {
        ServiceScope = _serviceScope ?? throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(serviceScope));
    }
}
```

And in the interceptor we could write something like:

```
var scopeAwareContext = new ScopeAwareServiceCallContext(serviceScope, context);
return await base.UnaryServerHandler(request, scopeAwareContext, continuation);
```

So, a riff on the decorator pattern, really.

Add to this an extension method on `ServiceCallContext` to try and extract the service scope, similarly to what you've written but in this case just trying to cast to `ScopeAwareServiceCallContext` instead of iterating on the headers, and you could have most of what you need:

```
public static class ServerCallContextDependencyInjectionExtensions
{
    public static IServiceProvider GetScopedServiceProvider(this ServerCallContext context)
    {
        if (context == null)
        {
            throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(context));
        }

        if (context is ScopeAwareServiceCallContext scopeAwareContext)
        {
            return scopeAwareContext.ServiceScope.ServiceProvider;
        }

        throw new ArgumentException(nameof(context));
    }
}
```

Ideally I'd like to have some sort of "context metadata" that one could add whatever one needs to (sort of like a view bag, as I've mentioned), but -- having a copy constructor on the (non-sealed!) `ServerCallContext` class -- all this could be solved just with extension methods. No new fields on the original `ServerCallContext` would need to be introduced. Neat & tidy -- I think.

This will quickly blow up if multiple interceptors each "swap" the server call context, but that's something that I can live with.

Now I get your idea of the copy ctor. That could work. I rather thought of replacing `ServerCallContext` with `IServiceProvider` and let the grpc internals look up the original `ServerCallContext` by invocation of `serviceProvider.GetRequiredService<ServerCallContext>()` . A developer could wrap the service provider without even having to know about the `ServerCallContext` existence.

A wrapping interceptor that does nothing would then look like:

```csharp
public override async Task<TResponse> UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>(TRequest request, IServiceProvider serviceProvider, UnaryServerMethod<TRequest, TResponse> continuation)
{
    return await base.UnaryServerHandler(request, serviceProvider, continuation);
}
```

And another one that adds a scope could look like:

```csharp
public override async Task<TResponse> UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>(TRequest request, IServiceProvider serviceProvider, UnaryServerMethod<TRequest, TResponse> continuation)
{
    using (var serviceScope = ServiceProvider.CreateScope())
    {
        return await base.UnaryServerHandler(request, serviceProvider, continuation);
    }
}
```

This means that dependency injection becomes a integrated component of the grpc csharp implementation.

I've run into the need to pass state between interceptors and call handlers myself. The state that I have is more than just an `IServiceProvider`, however.

I'd be happy to contribute either

1. "view-bag" on `ServerCallContext` or
1. unsealing `ServerCallContext` or adding an `IServerCallContext` interface

Would such a PR be accepted?

For the view-bag, my initial proposal is to add mutable property to server call context:

```csharp
/// <summary>Arbitrary state object associated with the call.</summary>
/// <remarks>
/// The gRPC library doesn't inspect or set this value. Your interceptors
/// and call handlers can use it how they see fit.
/// </remarks>
public object UserState { get; set; }
```

The view-bag is very simple to implement and is a pattern seen across various APIs in various languages and platforms (`void*` parameters on gRPC completion queues anyone? :smile:).

This could be extended to a `Dictionary<string, object>`. I believe this was considered during the initial C# interceptor development and rejected. Don't quite remember the details... Synchronization issues, maybe?

In any case, both a view-bag, subclass, or `IServerCallContext` approach would require collaboration between interceptors & call handlers and a cast from object/base. So, all these approaches basically have the same shape, so I'll defer to the library maintainers on which particular shape they want.

@dpsenner I am currently tunneling the `IServiceProvider` into the call handler with a similar interceptor. Instead of using a header, I use an [`AsyncLocal<IServiceProvider>`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.asynclocal-1?view=netcore-1.0):

```csharp
public static class ServerCallContextExtensions
{
    internal static AsyncLocal<IServiceProvider> ServiceProviderInstance { get; set; } = new AsyncLocal<IServiceProvider>();

    public static IServiceProvider ServiceProvider(this ServerCallContext _)
    {
        return ServiceProviderInstance.Value;
    }
}

// In the same assembly as ServerCallContextExtensions so it can access the internal field
public StartScopeInterceptor : Interceptor
{
    private readonly IServiceProvider _services;

    public StartScopeInterceptor(IServiceProvider services)
    {
        _services = services ?? throw ArgumentNullException(nameof(services));
    }

    public override async Task<TResponse> ClientStreamingServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>(
        IAsyncStreamReader<TRequest> requestStream,
        ServerCallContext context,
        ClientStreamingServerMethod<TRequest, TResponse> continuation)
    {
        using (var scope = _services.CreateScope())
        {
            ServerCallContextExtensions.ServiceProviderInstance.Value = scope.ServiceProvider;
            try
            {
                return await continuation(requestStream, context);
            }
            finally
            {
                ServerCallContextExtensions.ServiceProviderInstance.Value = null;
            }
        }
    }

    // ...
}

public ServiceImpl : TheService.TheServiceBase
{
    public override async Task<TheResponse> TheMethod(TheRequest request, ServerCallContext context)
    {
        IServiceProvider sp = context.ServiceProvider();
        // ...
    }
}
```

@chwarr yeah, `AsyncLocal` and extension methods look like the least-intrusive and "nicest" option ATM and `AsyncLocal` is used for this in a few other places -- the zipkin4net library uses a similar concept, for example, and that's how we added instrumentation for StackExchange.Redis.

Interesting info regarding the team possibly having considered a `Dictionary` at one point, by the way üëç I guess a `ConcurrentDictionary` could be used instead in case synchronization issues were a thing. But if an object is provided, then any library consumer could decide what they actually need.

I've actually had this lying around for a while now but never got around to actually running the test suite locally (to formally check that it doesn't break anything -- it really shouldn't though): https://github.com/cearny/grpc/commit/91bc5d6272e408372c5465552e452e4316af2cb9
